<h1>
<seg id="1">Šimon Ornest has declared: "In concert, we want to collect positive energy. "</seg>
</h1>
<p>
<seg id="2">That you think of the fact that in less than one month it should be the end of the world?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3">It is only one of this alarming news, the kind of traps in which we love to fall.</seg>
<seg id="4">In our group The Tap Tap, one rather laughs at it and one tells to itself than we are the only group capable of collecting a rest of positive energy in order to reject or of preventing the end of the world.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5">Furthermore, you go up in December a totally unique project: three concerts against the end of the world.</seg>
<seg id="6">Can you present more in detail this project to our readers?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="7">It is a charitable action that we prepare for already two years.</seg>
<seg id="8">We have decided to use the marketing potential of the end of the Maya calendar announced for December 21st at 11 hours 10 of the morning.</seg>
<seg id="9">The day before, on December 20th, three concerts will take place simultaneously, at Prague, Brno and Ostrava.</seg>
<seg id="10">They will end virtually at the moment where will take end the Maya calendar on the island of Kiribati that is found pacific in the ocean, on an hourly spindle early of 12 hours in relation to us.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="11">Who has had this idea?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="12">To the departure I think that it was my idea, afterwards we have conceived everything with our creator, Honza Augusta.</seg>
<seg id="13">Outside the fact that we want to collect sufficiently of positive energy to save the world, we want as together, with the public, to think about the state of the world as we leave to our children.</seg>
<seg id="14">On the Occasion of the end of the Maya calendar, we have created a collection of unique objects, notably of the shoes, T-shirts, bags, and of the original keys against the end of the world, buying them online on www.e-tap.cz the people can support us also.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="15">The group The Tap Tap with other interpreters also has recorded a hymn against the end of the world that is called "End of the world canceled" (in Czech" Konec světa zruseno ").</seg>
<seg id="16">It is already very popular on YouTube, one will hear it also during these charitable concerts?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="17">Of course, very in the end, finally, if we succeed and that the end of the world does not take place...</seg>
<seg id="18">It will be sung simultaneously by all the interpreters in the three concerts.</seg>
<seg id="19">The hymns will join also at a moment given within the framework of an emission in direct, totally unique, from the Czech television.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="20">The words of this song have been written by Tomás Hanák that has also the main role from Jesus in the clip, Xindl X sings also...</seg>
<seg id="21">How you are of it come to cooperate with them?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="22">We collaborate with other personalities of the Czech show-biz, because of the fact that we organize numerous concerts and charitable events...</seg>
<seg id="23">We endeavor to make them participate intensively in these projects.</seg>
<seg id="24">It has proved that most of them are interested by such a cooperation and that that amuses them.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="25">What will the profits of these concerts against the end of the world be used to?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="26">To equip the training center Studeo that is accessible to the people to reduced mobility and of which we work on the realization within the framework of the institute Jedlička, with the association Tap, and that for six years.</seg>
<seg id="27">Teachers go regularly next to the students of the institute Jedličkův and propose them activities that interest them and amuse them.</seg>
<seg id="28">The students themselves do not have the means of going to lessons, we try to help them in this way.</seg>
<seg id="29">Within the framework of the completion of the building of the institute Jedlička, we will transfer this project in a new independent building trade.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="30">Will several groups of music and interpreters go up on stage from these concerts during each?</seg>
<seg id="31">According to what criteria, you have the selected ones?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="32">We have tried to elaborate a program that appeals to all the generations, including the children.</seg>
<seg id="33">For example, in Prague, will go up on stage Chinaski, Support Lesbian, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.</seg>
<seg id="34">You will find all the details on www.kpks.cz.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="35">You prepare also for others " mega events" of this kind in the future?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="36">In May, we will play for the first time within the framework of the spring of Prague; there as, we will prepare surely a program of quality with interesting guests.</seg>
<seg id="37">We would love to play also the next year in the house of the Czech Republic in New York and personally, a time on site in the United States, I would love to combine well concerts to Washington and to Chicago.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="38">Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example at Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.</seg>
<seg id="39">Nevertheless The Tap Tap is a group composed of handicapped people.</seg>
<seg id="40">How do you manage the organization and the logistics of your rounds?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="41">It is not as terrible that that seems to the first surroundings.</seg>
<seg id="42">We have five members in electric armchair whose machines must travel in hold, naturally we drag around also many luggages and boxes of instruments....</seg>
<seg id="43">So far everything is itself more or less always well past, ČSA and British Airways always perfectly were prepared for us, they have surprised me more than one time.</seg>
<seg id="44">Even in Moscow, from where we have come back lately, everything has happened without problems.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="45">Thanks to your journeys abroad, you can compare in which these countries differ with regard to the easiness from access for the people to reduced mobility, of the attitude of the public opinion encounter of the people handicapped and so forth.</seg>
<seg id="46">What have been your experiences until now?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="47">After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and of other places where everything works better than at our places, we have precisely summer witnesses in Moscow that eastwards everyone is not although in an initial stage.</seg>
<seg id="48">In relation to Prague, Moscow is still very little accessible to the handicapped people; over there, it is not still a current that a person moves alone in electric armchair in the center of the city.</seg>
<seg id="49">They do not consider as an obviousness of giving a person the priority in armchair in an elevator yet.</seg>
<seg id="50">Fortunately, over there as, an association endeavoring to attract the attention on the problems of the handicapped people is at being created.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="51">In what must we still catch the more developed countries?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="52">There are many things for which we are still late...</seg>
<seg id="53">It is important to mention that the improvements and improvements depend always on the efforts deployed by the concerned people.</seg>
<seg id="54">At London and Madrid, it is totally ordinary that the people with a heavy handicap move alone in the public spaces; they can go to the bathroom, at the museum, anyplace...</seg>
<seg id="55">It is not nevertheless very frequent over there that a great number of handicapped people participate actively in the social life, on this point, you, The Tap Tap, are rather on the contrary to the point progress!</seg>
<seg id="56">The respect of the public and the easiness of access are a thing, but the situation will really start changing while we will have sportsmen, artists, actors, politicians or famous lawyers among us.</seg>
<seg id="57">For the time being, they are only isolated cases of people who have a strong will.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="58">The group The Tap Tap is presently very popular, let's return backward of some years, how much has driven you in 1998 to create this group?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="59">I have started working as teacher at the institute Jedlička, where I have found myself surrounded with many youths ready to be given oneself into something.</seg>
<seg id="60">And as I am myself musician (I play, among others, the saxophone), with a colleague, we have created a music activity.</seg>
<seg id="61">And then, with the time, as says our moderator Láďa Angelovič, one has lost the control of the situation (laughs) a bit.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="62">The success has happened only in the course of these last years, if I do not make a mistake?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="63">It is true, the fact of creating connections to well known singers and of working actively on the promotion of the group has helped us.</seg>
<seg id="64">We have understood that, if a work is not visible, it is as if it did not exist at heart.</seg>
<seg id="65">Thanks to the grants of the European Union, we can, besides, allow ourselves to have teachers of quality, of the equipment, and so forth.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="66">Did you have as objective to reach such a level with The Tap Tap?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="67">From the beginning, I have felt that there was a potential to change the things.</seg>
<seg id="68">The business show is full of things that are copied ones the others.</seg>
<seg id="69">In some way, it is logical: all what is new is accepted with caution and that long lasts.</seg>
<seg id="70">Rare are the original projects, and I dare to maintain that Tap Tap is one of them.</seg>
<seg id="71">The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is naturally the pity, it is natural...</seg>
<seg id="72">But the pity is totally useless, because the people with a handicap are not unwell beings, abandoned of everyone, which we must take in pity.</seg>
<seg id="73">They are people who can live a life fully and blossom itself, to condition of having the necessary means of course.</seg>
<seg id="74">I say often that while people with a handicap manage to realize something, it is not only an overhang for them but for the whole society.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="75">Your success also is not owed by the way that you are a leader requiring, as you are qualified by many people?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="76">If we want to do work of quality, we must be intransigent in many domains and require some discipline.</seg>
<seg id="77">But I think that it is totally normal.</seg>
<seg id="78">Some people arrive to our places with a romantic vision and the head in the clouds and, when they realize that they must come to the repetitions two times a week, to follow the preliminary lessons and to pass much of time on the roads for the concerts, they lose rapidly their enthusiasm.</seg>
<seg id="79">But that works in the same way in every group that wants to work and to reach objectives.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="80">The group The Tap Tap counts twenty members presently.</seg>
<seg id="81">How many of them were already there in 1998?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="82">Only one, Láďa Angelovič.</seg>
<seg id="83">We are an open group, the people go and leave, one can not nothing.</seg>
<seg id="84">Our doors are always open to those that want or would have desire of joining.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="85">That will be the case the day before of the day foreseen of the end of the world, on Thursday, December 2012 from 21 hours 20th.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="86">This action will take place in Prague in the arena Incheba, at Brno at Fléda and at Ostrava at the Plynojem with the participation of twelve groups and of other musicians of Czech Republic.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="87">In end of evening, these three cities will be connected by audiovisual intermediary while will be sung jointly the song of the group The Tap Tap "End of the world canceled".</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="88">The goal of the concert is of rallying average financiers (to height of 25 million CZK) to equip the training center multifunction Studeo that is in Prague in the institute Jedlička.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="89">The prize of a ticket for this concert is of 400 CZK, the entry is free for the children until 12 years, the presale of the tickets is open to Bohemiaticket.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
<DOC sysid="rbmt-4" docid="idnes.cz/2012/12/01/494025" genre="news" origlang="cs">
<h1>
<seg id="1">Poland and the cosmos.</seg>
</h1>
<p>
<seg id="2">Last week, during the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European spatial Agency, Poland has been admitted as twentieth member of this agency, it is the second Member State of the old block of the East (the Czech Republic has become member fully on November 12th, 2008).</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3">Poland had started a narrow collaboration with the ESA in 1994 and in the course of the years that have followed has participated in a number of projects of the agency.</seg>
<seg id="4">The road of Poland to the space has begun though much earlier.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5">Already before the second world war, passionate Polish worked on spatial flights; they did always not meet understanding.</seg>
<seg id="6">I would want to evoke for example the conference of A. Šternfeld to the astronomical observatory of Warsaw, on December 6th, 1933, in the course of which he presented ideas gotten out of his work of avant-garde titled "Introduction to the astronautics".</seg>
<seg id="7">The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the cold listeners and of the years later Šternfeld remembered than only the doctor Jan Gadomski was interested in his works.</seg>
<seg id="8">In 1934, Šternfeld obtained in France the price Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his work "Introduction to the astronautics".</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="9">The aforementioned doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) became thereafter a great spread of the astronomy and of the astronautics.</seg>
<seg id="10">It published hundreds of articles in the Polish newspapers and wrote numerous works devoted to this scientific discipline.</seg>
<seg id="11">Gadomski has become a spread of the astronautics of world fame, his contribution has notably been rewarded with the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="12">From 1925 was built in Poland an intended gang car to be equipped with a rocket motor.</seg>
<seg id="13">One does not know unfortunately either the author or the details of this project.</seg>
<seg id="14">It is not clear either if the rocket had to be used to propel or to slow down the gang car.</seg>
<seg id="15">The only information known on this gang car are those of the press of the time.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="16">From 1933, the Polish artillery started devoting itself to the rockets.</seg>
<seg id="17">The investigations were led by the institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with the teachers Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.</seg>
<seg id="18">It emerges from the preserved documents that this research had reached the stadium of the testings.</seg>
<seg id="19">Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the investigations have interrupted themselves.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="20">In 1937, the plans of a rocket of photoelectric hunting, outlined by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and next year was published the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" of an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.</seg>
<seg id="21">These two projects had a military use of the motors of rockets as purpose.</seg>
<seg id="22">Just before the war, all the projects of use of the technique of the rockets were led by the provisional consultative scientific committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the works.</seg>
<seg id="23">This committee had been created in 1937, but after two years of working, the beginning of the war put an end to his activities.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="24">After the war, other works devoted to the aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronautic society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).</seg>
<seg id="25">For the first time, it is question of a society in the number of November 1954 of the Problem newspaper, in which four more detailed articles devoted to the aeronautics are.</seg>
<seg id="26">In one of these articles, written by the teacher Mr. Subotowicze, it is proposed of creating a society devoted to the astronautics</seg>
<seg id="27">At this time, projects of artificial satellites had already been launched and it was light that the domain of the spatial research had of the future.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="28">At the beginning of the year 1956, the Polish astronautic society (PTA) deployed efforts to enter to the international astronautic federation (created in 1951) and from the autumn, the PTA became a regular member.</seg>
<seg id="29">Next year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the international astronautic federation.</seg>
<seg id="30">It preserved his duty up to his death in 1959.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="31">From 1956, the PTA brought a significant contribution to the crowned development of success of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific investigations.</seg>
<seg id="32">The first model, RM-1, was finished in 1957 and the first launching took place on October 10th, 1958.</seg>
<seg id="33">This rocket of a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a bit less than 5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="34">Thereafter was built an improved version, RM-1A and, for the summer 1959, of the testings of flight of the rocket to two stories RM-2 were started in the desert of Bledov.</seg>
<seg id="35">This rocket had a length of 1.4 meter and probably weighed 11.5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="36">The next prototype should have been capable of carrying out concrete scientific works - the rocket RM-34 should have had a range going up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind in altitude.</seg>
<seg id="37">But in 1963, all the works of development were stopped.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="38">The rocket Meteor-1 designed in the course of the period 1962 - 1965, followed the first rockets of type RM.</seg>
<seg id="39">This rocket, conceived with two stories, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="40">Three models (called Meteor-1A -1 B and -1 C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved to the scientific tools.</seg>
<seg id="41">The rocket Meteor-1A had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liter, while in Meteor-1B this volume was of 0.34 liter and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 liter.</seg>
<seg id="42">The maximal range of all these types of machine was of 37 km.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="43">In the period 1965 - 1968, the rockets Meteor-2 were designed in the aeronautical institute, the first testings of flight began in October 1970.</seg>
<seg id="44">The rocket Meteor-2 had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of transporting a load useful of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.</seg>
<seg id="45">Thereafter were built the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="46">It suits still to mention the entry of Poland the COSPAR (Committee heart Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national committee COSPAR two years more late.</seg>
<seg id="47">Within the framework of the program Interkosmos, Poland has also participated in the spatial exploration on the artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
