<seg id="9">But I also think that neither it does not support the American position.</seg>
<seg id="10">Germany wanted to assert his independence, without though appearing too critical to Israel.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="11">During the insurrection in Libya of March 2011, Germany had also chosen the abstention during the vote on the arrangement of a zone of aerial exclusion.</seg>
<seg id="12">Finally, the NATO imposed this measure.</seg>
<seg id="13">Does Germany have difficulties to adopting a clear position about the great international questions?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="14">The reply is yes.</seg>
<seg id="15">The reason is that Berlin is revising his exterior policy, trying to move away of a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to institute a German exterior policy.</seg>
<seg id="16">Furthermore, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.</seg>
<seg id="17">The Germans collide therefore with several foreheads.</seg>
<seg id="18">One expects from them that they play a more independent role, but they are not to it accustomed.</seg>
<seg id="19">I believe that they grope around still to find this role, but are on the way of a "more normal" foreign policy.</seg>
<seg id="20">An exterior policy, as in France or in Great Britain</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="21">That means then concretely the term of "normal" foreign policy for the Germans?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="22">It shows the will of adopting positions independent from those of the United States and of the European partners, including in what concerns the national files.</seg>
<seg id="23">I believe that the German foreign policy is also determined by his economic policy, therefore by the exportations and his relationships with some regions, as Russia, China or the Middle East.</seg>
<seg id="24">The German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers: it is why Germany must protect his interests.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="25">These economic interests have influenced the position of Germany in relation to the conflict in the Middle East and the abstention during the vote of the United Nations?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="26">Germany has first important openings in Middle East, especially in the countries of the Gulf.</seg>
<seg id="27">It is why Berlin must watch out not to strike the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arabic countries.</seg>
<seg id="28">It is there undoubtedly a matter of a determiner element.</seg>
<seg id="29">However, I would not match too much importance to it, because it is not a matter of exclusively unilateral relationship.</seg>
<seg id="30">But it is in any case a determiner element there in the German strategic thoughts.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="31">Does Germany harm his relationships with the United States choosing the abstention during important votes, as in the case of Palestine?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="32">I think that the Europeans and the Americans understand the German position perfectly.</seg>
<seg id="33">It is why I think that the fracture is not so serious as it was it in the case of the Libyan question.</seg>
<seg id="34">Maybe even that Germany will not be respected only anymore.</seg>
<seg id="35">Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as international actor and that his interests must be taken into account.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="36">In Europe, the opinions regarding the Palestinian initiative are diverse.</seg>
<seg id="37">On the other hand, the United States have announced their veto of a clear voice.</seg>
