<seg id="41">But considering the political shape of the country, the government can not defend of course his position publicly.</seg>
<seg id="42">I believe that the real differences of opinions are not so big as they seem it always.</seg>
<seg id="43">If you observe the relationships between Obama and the Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm with regard to the policy of Netanyahou.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="44">Does Germany have difficulties to reconciling his narrow relationships with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the great European partners, on the other hand?</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="45">I think that that does not facilitate the things for the Germans.</seg>
<seg id="46">Evidently, it would be a bit simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and regular European policy, but today, it is not the case.</seg>
<seg id="47">They can therefore not register themselves within a vaster political line and must assert their singular position.</seg>
<seg id="48">It is what they make presently in the question of the euro.</seg>
